│ (e.g., because the shuffled vector lane is known to be zero),                 │
│ CreateExtractElement returns a Constant, not an instruction. The subsequent   │
│ cast<ExtractElementInst> triggers an assertion when given a Value of          │
│ incompatible type, leading to the abort.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe log  │
│ shows the first transformation replaced a shuffle with a constant vector:     │
│ %shift gets replaced by <4 x i64> <i64 0, i64 undef, i64 undef, i64 undef>.   │
│ Immediately after, VectorCombine visits the 'or' instruction and attempts     │
│ foldExtractExtract, which calls translateExtract. Given the IR, extelt        │
│ %shuffle.1, 1 extracts a lane that is effectively constant 0 due to the       │
│ construction of %shuffle.1 from zeroinitializer. Thus, the translate creates  │
│ a shuffle and immediately an extract which the builder constant folds into a  │
│ Constant, not an instruction.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\ntranslateExtract    │
│ has a guard to avoid creating instructions if X is a Constant, but it does    │
│ not guard against constant-folding of the created extract itself. In cases    │
│ like the reproducer, the vector operand X is non-constant, but the specific   │
│ extracted lane is provably constant after the inserted shuffle. Therefore     │
│ Builder.CreateExtractElement(...) may return a Constant. The code then        │
│ performs cast<ExtractElementInst>(...) unconditionally, violating the cast    │
│ precondition and crashing.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nEdit                │
│ translateExtract to handle the case where CreateExtractElement returns a      │
│ Constant. Use dyn_cast and return nullptr if it is not an                     │
│ ExtractElementInst.\n\nEdit at                                                │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VectorCombine.cpp lines 559-567:\n- Current:\n  │
